## `impl fuser::Filesystem for Adapter`
<!-- checksum: rust-fuse-2 -->

### Postconditions — callback inventory

Same 27 callbacks as the Python port (adapter.py.engspec § callback inventory table). Every callback wraps:

```rust
fn lookup(&mut self, req: &Request, parent: u64, name: &OsStr, reply: ReplyEntry) {
    let name_str = match name.to_str() {
        Some(s) => s,
        None => { reply.error(libc::EINVAL); return; }
    };
    // Enter caller identity
    let _guard = self.fs.as_user(req.uid(), req.gid());
    // Path reconstruction: fuser gives us (parent_inode, name); library
    // wants a full path. Use fs.path_of_inode to walk up from parent,
    // then append name.
    let parent_path = match self.fs.path_of_inode(parent) {
        Some(p) => p,
        None => { reply.error(libc::ENOENT); return; }
    };
    let child_path = if parent_path == "/" {
        format!("/{name_str}")
    } else {
        format!("{parent_path}/{name_str}")
    };
    match self.fs.stat(&child_path, false) {
        Ok(st) => {
            let attr = self.stat_to_attr(&st);
            reply.entry(&TTL, &attr, 0);
        }
        Err(e) => reply.error(e.errno()),
    }
}
```

The same pattern repeats for every callback. To avoid 30 near-identical snippets in this engspec, the **Implementation Notes for each callback live in the Rust code itself** — this engspec describes the pattern and the invariants, and the regenerator writes the boilerplate.

### Callbacks implemented (27, from plan.v4 inventory):

- `getattr`, `setattr`, `lookup`, `forget` (no-op in v1)
- `mkdir`, `rmdir`, `unlink`
- `opendir`, `readdir`, `releasedir`
- `open`, `create`, `read`, `write`, `release`, `flush`, `fsync`, `fsyncdir`
- `readlink`, `symlink`, `link`, `rename`
- `setxattr`, `getxattr`, `listxattr`, `removexattr`
- `access`, `statfs`

### NOT implemented (explicit negative boundaries):

- `mknod` — no special files (FIFOs, sockets, devices).
- `ioctl`, `poll`, `bmap`, `fallocate` — deferred.
- `write_buf` / `read_buf` — default read/write suffices.
- Lock callbacks — `fuser` surfaces them as `getlk`/`setlk`/`setlkw`; the library `LockManager` would need wiring. Deferred to v2.

### Error translation

Every callback ends with the equivalent of:

```rust
match result {
    Ok(v)  => reply.<variant>(...),
    Err(e) => reply.error(e.errno()),
}
```

`e.errno()` is defined on the library `Error` enum (see `errors.rs.engspec`). No trait-object / catch-unwind overhead.

### Test Strategy

The adapter is validated via real FUSE mount tests in `tests/`, gated behind `#[cfg(feature = "fuse")]`:

```rust
#[cfg(feature = "fuse")]
#[test]
fn mount_roundtrip() {
    // 1. mkfs a temp DB.
    // 2. Spawn mount in a thread (fuser::mount2).
    // 3. Wait for /proc/self/mountinfo to show the mount.
    // 4. Perform POSIX ops via std::fs.
    // 5. Call fusermount3 -u.
    // 6. Assert all ops succeeded and the DB is consistent.
}
```

Interop tests with git/rsync/tar mirror the Python harness.

